Every time

### What version of React are you using?

19.2.0

### What version of React Compiler are you using?

1.0.0

## Summary

Fixes #34752, #34194, #35762

### The bug

The compiler hoists property accesses from inside closures (event handlers, hook callbacks, returned functions) into memoization cache key checks that run during render. When the base object is nullable, this causes a runtime `TypeError` — even though the user's source code is perfectly safe.

For example, this cart page from the [iFixit workaround PR](https://github.com/iFixit/ifixit/pull/61341):

```tsx
function CartPageView() {
  const cart = useCart(); // cart.data is null until loaded
  const [promoCode, setPromoCode] = useState('');

  const handleCheckout = async () => {
    await processPayment({
      price: cart.data.totals.price,
      itemCount: cart.data.lineItems.length,
      promoCode,
    });
  };

  if (!cart.data) return <CartSkeleton />;

  return (
    <div>
      <LineItems items={cart.data.lineItems} />
      <span>{cart.data.totals.price}</span>
      <input value={promoCode} onChange={e => setPromoCode(e.target.value)} />
      <button onClick={handleCheckout}>Checkout</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The source code is safe: `handleCheckout` only runs when the user clicks, and the `if (!cart.data) return` guard prevents the button from rendering while the cart is loading. [But the compiler generates:](https://playground.react.dev/#-xZFwR8Eo7wlRgyk5wgyDMw83yqlvnnvugImAAWQhdYeBAI1TFAvgVTAP8wH7BAjAXKAl0wVd10KHIu3AYoIBYD4rAQFkjTAFA0GI80gA)

```js
const cart = useCart();
const [promoCode, setPromoCode] = useState("");

// Cache check runs BEFORE the null guard — crashes when cart.data is null
if (
  $[0] !== cart.data.lineItems.length ||  // TypeError
  $[1] !== cart.data.totals.price ||
  $[2] !== promoCode
) {
  t0 = async () => { /* ... */ };
  $[0] = cart.data.lineItems.length;
  $[1] = cart.data.totals.price;
  // ...
}

// The null guard comes AFTER — too late
if (!cart.data) return <CartSkeleton />;
```

The compiler saw `cart.data.totals.price` and `cart.data.lineItems.length` inside `handleCheckout`, concluded that `cart.data` must be non-null, and hoisted those property accesses into render-time cache keys. But `handleCheckout` doesn't run during render — it runs later when the user clicks. The non-null assumption is invalid.

Note that the render-time code after the null guard is fine — `cart.data.lineItems` and `cart.data.totals.price` in the JSX are correctly guarded and the compiler handles them properly.

iFixit worked around this by extracting nullable accesses into local variables with `?? null` and adding `?.` at every level:

```tsx
// Workaround: extract to local variable and guard every level
const cartData = cart.data ?? null;
const cartPrice = cartData?.totals?.price;
```

This same bug manifests across their codebase in patterns like:
- `bottomMenu?.items.map(...)` — had to change to `bottomMenu?.items?.map(...)`
- `section.tags?.split(',').map(...)` — had to change to `section.tags?.split(',')?.map(...)`
- `cart.data?.lineItems.find(...)` — had to extract to local variable

### Root cause

`getAssumedInvokedFunctions` in `CollectHoistablePropertyLoads.ts` builds a set of inner functions whose property accesses are treated as proof of non-null at render time. The problem: it put **all** inner functions into a single set — both functions that genuinely execute during render (direct calls like `const v = fn()`) and functions that execute later (JSX event handlers, hook callbacks, returned functions).

`collectNonNullsInBlocks` then walked into every "assumed invoked" function, collected all property accesses as `assumedNonNullObjects`, and propagated them to the outer render scope. This told downstream passes that `cart.data` was unconditionally non-null, which:

1. Caused `reduceMaybeOptionalChains` to strip `?.` to `.` in dependency paths
2. Caused `DeriveMinimalDependenciesHIR` to use `cart.data.totals.price` (deep path) instead of `cart.data` (truncated path) as the cache key
3. Caused `codegenDependency` to emit `cart.data.totals.price` as a non-optional cache key check

### The fix (two parts)

#### Part 1: Split sync vs deferred invocation (`CollectHoistablePropertyLoads.ts`)

Split `assumedInvokedFns` into two categories:

- **`syncInvoked`**: Direct function calls (`const v = fn()`) — these execute during render, so if they access `cart.data.totals.price`, that does prove `cart.data` is non-null at render time. Safe to propagate `assumedNonNullObjects` to the outer scope.
- **`deferredInvoked`**: JSX props/children (`<Btn onClick={fn}>`), hook arguments (`useEffect(fn)`), returned functions (`return fn`) — these execute later, so their property accesses tell us nothing about render-time nullability. NOT safe to propagate as non-null proofs.

Both categories are still recursed into for their own internal scope memoization — a deferred closure still gets its own optimized cache keys internally. The only change is that deferred closures no longer leak their non-null assumptions outward.

The transitive closure also respects categories: if a sync function calls another function, that callee is sync. If a deferred function calls another function, that callee is deferred. If a function is reachable from both, sync wins (it does execute during render).

#### Part 2: Preserve fine-grained cache keys via optional access (`DeriveMinimalDependenciesHIR.ts`)

After Part 1 alone, deferred closure dependency paths would be **truncated** to the base object (e.g. `cart.data.totals.price` becomes just `cart.data` in the cache key). This is safe but loses memoization granularity — if `cart.data` is a new object on every render but `cart.data.totals.price` stays `29.99`, the cache would miss every time with `cart.data` (reference equality) but would hit with `cart.data.totals.price` (value equality).

To preserve fine-grained memoization, deferred closure property paths are now tracked in a separate `deferredNonNullObjects` set that flows through `BlockInfo` and into `ReactiveScopeDependencyTreeHIR` as a secondary hoistable tree. When `addDependency()` would normally truncate a path because the base isn't in the main hoistable tree, it checks the deferred tree as a fallback. If the path exists there, it emits **optional access** instead of truncating:

```js
// Before (main — crashes):
if (
  $[0] !== cart.data.lineItems.length ||
  $[1] !== cart.data.totals.price ||
  $[2] !== promoCode
) {

// After Part 1 only (safe but coarse — reference equality):
if (
  $[0] !== cart.data ||
  $[1] !== promoCode
) {

// After Part 2 (safe AND fine-grained — value equality via optional access):
if (
  $[0] !== cart.data?.lineItems?.length ||
  $[1] !== cart.data?.totals?.price ||
  $[2] !== promoCode
) {
```

`cart.data?.totals?.price` evaluates to `undefined` when `cart.data` is null (no crash), and still tracks changes to the specific price value when `cart.data` is non-null (fine-grained memoization).

This improvement is **scoped to deferred closures only**. Render-time truncation (e.g. try-catch blocks, jump-poisoned scopes) is preserved because those paths aren't in the deferred tree. Sync paths (direct function calls during render) are also unaffected and retain fully unconditional cache keys.

## Test plan

- [x] 10 new bug fixture tests covering: nullable prop + onClick, TS non-null assertion, mixed optional chains, nested properties, useEffectEvent pattern, hook arguments, assertion functions, multiple closures, conditional render access, returned functions
- [x] 2 correctness guard fixtures confirming sync paths (direct calls, render-time accesses) are preserved
- [x] All 1730 existing compiler tests pass
- [x] 38 existing snapshot updates reviewed — all show safe cache key changes for deferred paths (e.g. `obj` to `obj?.value`)
- [x] `direct-call` and `conditional-call` fixtures unchanged (sync paths preserved)
- [x] `try-catch-maybe-null-dependency`, `jump-poisoned/*`, and `merge-uncond-optional-chain-and-cond` fixtures unchanged (render-time truncation preserved)
